SUDO permission: sudo (Super User DO) command in Linux is generally used as a prefix of some command that only superuser are allowed to run. If you prefix sudo with any command, it will run that command with elevated privileges or in other words allow a user with proper permissions to execute a command as another user, such as the superuser. This is the equivalent of "run as administrator" option in Windows.
The option of sudo lets us have multiple administrators. To allow user to use sudo command, user must be listed in "/etc/sudoers" file. Or user should belong to wheel group. Wheel group is default group which allow users to use sudo command. 
Syntax, 
# sudo <command_Line> 
Examples, 
[root----------------------------------------------->  su - amit 
[amit----------------------------------------------->  useradd shubham 
-bash: /usr/sbin/useradd: Permission denied 
[amit-----------------------------------------------> sudo useradd shubham 

Visudo   = /etc/sudoers

Usermod -aG sudo <username>
